---
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro"
import Header from "../components/Header.astro"
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro"
import { fetchPageStats } from "../lib/bucket"
import "../styles/global.css"

const stats = await fetchPageStats("needles")
const wasteStats = await fetchPageStats("waste")
const rs = (wasteStats as Record<string, any>)?.routing_stats as
	| { closed_no_action_pct: number; bpw_rejection_pct: number; contractor_dispatch_pct: number }
	| undefined
---

<BaseLayout
	title="What Happens After You Report Human Waste in Boston — Boston Urban Hazard Maps"
	description="You file a 311 report. The city closes it. The waste is still there. Here's what the data shows about how Boston handles — and loses — human waste complaints."
	canonical="https://www.urbanhazardmaps.com/data-quality"
>
	<Header generated={stats.generated} />

	<main class="container" style="padding-top: 32px; padding-bottom: 48px;">
		<nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
			<a href="/">Home</a> <span aria-hidden="true">/</span> <span>Data Quality</span>
		</nav>

		<h1 class="page-title">What Happens After You Report Human Waste in Boston</h1>
		<p class="page-subtitle">
			You see human feces on the sidewalk. You open the 311 app and file a report.
			You expect someone to come clean it up. Here's what actually happens —
			based on every public record the city has released.
		</p>

		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<!-- SECTION 1: Your ticket gets closed, nothing happens -->
		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2 class="section-title">1. Your Report Gets Closed — But Nothing Happens</h2>
			<div class="card prose">
				<p>
					"Closed" in Boston's 311 system does not mean "resolved." It means the
					ticket was marked complete — even when the receiving department had no
					way to act on it or send it to someone who could. For human waste reports,
					the data tells a stark story:
				</p>
				{rs && (
					<div class="stats-grid">
						<div class="stat-item stat-bad">
							<span class="stat-number">{rs.closed_no_action_pct.toFixed(1)}%</span>
							<span class="stat-desc">closed with no evidence of action</span>
						</div>
						<div class="stat-item">
							<span class="stat-number">{rs.bpw_rejection_pct.toFixed(1)}%</span>
							<span class="stat-desc">rejected — "BPW does not service human waste"</span>
						</div>
						<div class="stat-item">
							<span class="stat-number">{rs.contractor_dispatch_pct.toFixed(1)}%</span>
							<span class="stat-desc">sent to outside contractor (no follow-up)</span>
						</div>
					</div>
				)}
				<div class="example-box">
					<div class="example-title">Real ticket — 5 reports, same morning</div>
					<div class="example-content">
						<div class="example-field">
							<span class="field-label">Closure note:</span>
							"BPW does not service human waste on public streets. Case was sent
							to outside contractor"
						</div>
						<div class="example-field">
							<span class="field-label">Result:</span>
							All 5 tickets bulk-closed between 7:01 AM and 7:54 AM on May 20, 2025.
							No contractor response recorded. No confirmation the waste was cleaned.
						</div>
					</div>
					<p class="example-note">
						Five residents reported a problem. The city's data says all five are "resolved."
						The closure note says the department that received the tickets can't handle them.
					</p>
				</div>
				<p>
					Many other waste tickets have no closure reason at all — just an empty field
					and a closed status. The ticket disappears from the queue without any
					record of what happened.
				</p>
				<div class="fix-box">
					<strong>What should change:</strong> Closed tickets with rejection language
					("does not service," "sent to contractor") should automatically reopen or
					escalate — not count as resolved. A simple text check on closure notes
					could catch this today.
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<!-- SECTION 2: There's no button for human waste -->
		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2 class="section-title">2. There's No Button for Human Waste</h2>
			<div class="card prose">
				<p>
					Boston's 311 app has 162+ ticket types. Not one of them is "human waste,"
					"biohazard," or anything close. When you report feces on the sidewalk,
					you pick the closest thing you can find: <strong>"Requests for Street Cleaning."</strong>
				</p>
				<p>
					That means your biohazard report gets routed to a street sweeper. The crew
					that shows up isn't equipped for it. The ticket either gets rejected
					("BPW does not service human waste") or silently closed.
				</p>
				<div class="example-box">
					<div class="example-title">What a resident actually reported</div>
					<div class="example-content">
						<div class="example-field">
							<span class="field-label">Category selected:</span> Requests for Street Cleaning
						</div>
						<div class="example-field">
							<span class="field-label">What they wrote:</span>
							"BIOHAZARD! Gentleman decided the sidewalk next to my house looked like
							a nice place to have a bowel movement. Although it may look like just
							urine, it is not. Please clean this up."
						</div>
						<div class="example-field">
							<span class="field-label">City's response:</span>
							"Case Resolved the site was cleaned"
						</div>
					</div>
					<p class="example-note">
						This resident clearly described a biohazard. The system categorized it as
						street cleaning because no better option exists. In the city's data,
						this is indistinguishable from a request to sweep leaves.
					</p>
				</div>
				<p>
					Other cities have solved this.
					<a href="https://sf311.org/services/human-animal-waste" target="_blank" rel="noopener">San Francisco</a>
					added a "Human or Animal Waste" category in 2008 with a 12–24 hour SLA.
					<a href="https://www.portland.gov/transportation/maintenance/report-biohazard" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Portland</a>
					routes biohazards to a dedicated team. Boston's 311 system is currently
					<a href="/fix">migrating to new software</a> — this is the window to add it.
				</p>
				<div class="fix-box">
					<strong>What should change:</strong> Add a "Human Waste / Biohazard" category
					to the 311 app. Route it to the correct response team — not street sweeping.
					This is a configuration change, not a technology problem.
					<a href="/fix">See our full proposal →</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<!-- SECTION 3: Waste never reaches the right team -->
		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2 class="section-title">3. The Waste Never Reaches the Right Team</h2>
			<div class="card prose">
				<p>
					Here's the routing chain for a human waste report in Boston:
				</p>
				<ol class="routing-chain">
					<li>Resident reports "feces on sidewalk" via 311 app</li>
					<li>No matching category → resident selects "Street Cleaning"</li>
					<li>Ticket goes to Bureau of Public Works (BPW) street sweeping</li>
					<li>BPW closes it: "does not service human waste on public streets"</li>
					<li>Some tickets note "sent to outside contractor" — but no contractor ticket is created</li>
					<li>No department is accountable. No SLA. No follow-up.</li>
				</ol>
				<p>
					Workers who receive these tickets have no way to reroute them. The
					system gives them one option: close it. The report goes to the wrong
					team, and the rejection is counted as a resolution. There is no
					department in Boston's 311 system whose job it is to handle human
					waste on public streets.
				</p>
				<div class="fix-box">
					<strong>What should change:</strong> Assign a response team for human waste.
					Whether that's a city crew, a contracted vendor, or an extension of the
					existing needle cleanup program — someone needs to own it. Right now, no one does.
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<!-- SECTION 4: People report the same spot over and over -->
		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2 class="section-title">4. People Report the Same Spot Over and Over</h2>
			<div class="card prose">
				<p>
					When a report gets closed without action, some residents try again.
					Same location, same problem, new ticket. These repeat reporters are a
					signal — they represent the fraction of people frustrated enough to go
					through the process twice. Most people give up after the first time.
				</p>
				<p>
					We're building an analysis to detect these "frustration clusters" —
					locations with multiple reports for the same problem within a short window.
					Each cluster is evidence of a systemic failure: a place where the city's
					process isn't working and residents know it.
				</p>
				<div class="impact-box">
					<strong>Coming soon:</strong> We're developing a model to identify repeat-report
					locations and measure how many attempts it takes before a problem gets resolved —
					if it ever does. Follow our progress on
					<a href="https://github.com/urban-hazards/urban-hazard-maps/issues/47"
						target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>.
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<!-- SECTION 5: The city strips the most useful field -->
		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2 class="section-title">5. The City Strips the Most Useful Field from Public Data</h2>
			<div class="card prose">
				<p>
					When you write a description in your 311 report — "human feces on the
					sidewalk" or "needles in the park near the playground" — that text is
					the most important part of the record. It's where the real information is.
				</p>
				<p>
					<strong>Boston removes this field entirely from the public data export.</strong>
					The dataset on
					<a href="https://data.boston.gov/dataset/311-service-requests" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Analyze Boston</a>
					includes timestamps, location, department, and closure reason — but the
					original description is gone. Zero percent of records have it.
				</p>
				<p>
					The description <em>does</em> exist in a separate system — the
					<a href="https://boston2-production.spotmobile.net/open311/v2/services.json"
						target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open311 API</a> —
					but you have to request each ticket individually. There's no bulk endpoint.
					We enrich targeted records this way for our
					<a href="/methodology">waste classifier</a>, but it's slow and incomplete.
				</p>
				<p>
					Without descriptions, anyone analyzing this data — journalists, researchers,
					the city itself — is working blind. You can't find human waste reports
					by reading "Requests for Street Cleaning." You need the text the resident wrote.
				</p>
				<div class="fix-box">
					<strong>What should change:</strong> Include the description field in the
					public data export, with personal information redacted. Other cities
					publish descriptions. Boston already publishes the closure reason — the
					original report deserves the same treatment.
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<!-- SECTION 6: Missing and inconsistent data -->
		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2 class="section-title">6. Missing and Inconsistent Data</h2>
			<div class="card prose">
				<p>
					Even the fields that are published have gaps. In the 2024 street cleaning
					data (22,539 records):
				</p>
				<div class="stats-grid">
					<div class="stat-item">
						<span class="stat-number">24.3%</span>
						<span class="stat-desc">missing zip code</span>
					</div>
					<div class="stat-item">
						<span class="stat-number">5.3%</span>
						<span class="stat-desc">missing close date (can't compute response time)</span>
					</div>
					<div class="stat-item">
						<span class="stat-number">0.02%</span>
						<span class="stat-desc">missing GPS coordinates</span>
					</div>
				</div>
				<p>
					Category names change over time — "Needle Pickup," "Needle Clean-up," and
					"Needle Cleanup" are three different strings for the same service. "Encampments"
					only appears starting in 2025. Our pipeline normalizes these, but any analysis
					that doesn't will undercount.
				</p>
				<p>
					Timestamps don't include timezone information. The structured data appears
					to be in UTC, but closure notes include Eastern time. Without conversion,
					it looks like Boston's peak 311 reporting hour is 4 AM — which makes no sense.
					After converting to Eastern, the peak shifts to late morning. Our pipeline
					now handles this conversion, but any downstream consumer of the raw data
					who doesn't know about the offset will get wrong results.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<!-- SECTION 7: Open311 API exposes personal info -->
		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2 class="section-title">7. The Backup API Exposes Personal Information</h2>
			<div class="card prose">
				<p>
					The Open311 API at <code>boston2-production.spotmobile.net</code> — the same
					one we use to retrieve stripped descriptions — returns reporter names, email
					addresses, and phone numbers when queried with <code>?extensions=true</code>.
					No API key required. Anyone who knows the endpoint can access it.
				</p>
				<p>
					<strong>We do not store, display, or use any personal information.</strong>
					Our pipeline reads only the description field for classification. But the
					fact that PII is openly accessible is a privacy issue the city should address.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<!-- What this means -->
		<!-- ============================================ -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2 class="section-title">What This Means</h2>
			<div class="card prose">
				<p>
					Every number on this site is an undercount. Records without coordinates
					get dropped. Reports filed under wrong categories get missed. Descriptions
					that would help classification are stripped from the public data.
					"Closed" doesn't mean "resolved." And there's no way to know how many
					people saw a problem, thought about reporting it, and didn't bother.
				</p>
				<p>
					These aren't obscure technical bugs — they're design choices that make it
					impossible to see how the city handles human waste on public streets. The
					data exists. The infrastructure exists. What's missing is the configuration
					and the accountability.
				</p>
				<p>
					We publish our <a href="/methodology">methodology</a> and
					<a href="https://github.com/urban-hazards/urban-hazard-maps"
						target="_blank" rel="noopener">source code</a> so you can verify
					everything here. If you find something we got wrong,
					<a href="https://github.com/urban-hazards/urban-hazard-maps/discussions"
						target="_blank" rel="noopener">let us know</a>.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; justify-content: center; margin-top: 32px; flex-wrap: wrap;">
			<a href="/fix" class="nav-link">How to fix this &rarr;</a>
			<a href="/methodology" class="nav-link">How the classifier works &rarr;</a>
			<a href="/" class="nav-link">&larr; Back to the map</a>
		</div>
	</main>

	<Footer />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
	.breadcrumb {
		font-size: var(--fs-sm);
		color: var(--color-text-muted);
		margin-bottom: var(--sp-md);
	}

	.breadcrumb a {
		color: var(--color-blue);
	}

	.breadcrumb span {
		margin: 0 4px;
	}

	.page-title {
		font-size: var(--fs-2xl);
		margin-bottom: 8px;
		position: relative;
		padding-bottom: 16px;
	}

	.page-title::after {
		content: "";
		position: absolute;
		bottom: 0;
		left: 0;
		width: 60px;
		height: 3px;
		background: var(--color-accent);
		border-radius: 2px;
	}

	.page-subtitle {
		font-size: var(--fs-md);
		line-height: 1.7;
		color: var(--color-text-muted);
		margin-bottom: var(--sp-xl);
		max-width: 900px;
	}

	.prose {
		line-height: 1.8;
		font-size: var(--fs-base);
		color: var(--color-text-muted);
		border-left: 3px solid var(--color-teal);
	}

	.prose p {
		margin-bottom: 14px;
	}

	.prose p:last-child {
		margin-bottom: 0;
	}

	.prose ol,
	.prose ul {
		margin: 12px 0;
		padding-left: 24px;
	}

	.prose li {
		margin-bottom: 8px;
	}

	.prose em {
		background: var(--color-accent-light);
		padding: 1px 4px;
		border-radius: 3px;
		font-style: normal;
		font-size: var(--fs-sm);
		font-family: monospace;
	}

	.prose code {
		background: var(--color-surface-alt);
		border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);
		padding: 1px 5px;
		border-radius: 3px;
		font-size: var(--fs-sm);
	}

	.routing-chain {
		background: var(--color-surface-alt);
		border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);
		border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
		padding: 16px 16px 16px 36px;
		margin: 14px 0;
		font-size: var(--fs-sm);
		line-height: 1.8;
	}

	.routing-chain li {
		padding-left: 4px;
	}

	.routing-chain li::marker {
		font-weight: 700;
		color: var(--color-text);
	}

	.impact-box {
		background: #e8f4fd;
		border: 1px solid #b8daff;
		border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
		padding: 12px 16px;
		margin: 14px 0;
		font-size: var(--fs-sm);
		line-height: 1.6;
		color: #0c5460;
	}

	.fix-box {
		background: #d4edda;
		border: 1px solid #28a745;
		border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
		padding: 12px 16px;
		margin: 14px 0;
		font-size: var(--fs-sm);
		line-height: 1.6;
		color: #155724;
	}

	.example-box {
		background: var(--color-surface-alt);
		border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);
		border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
		padding: 16px;
		margin: 14px 0;
	}

	.example-title {
		font-size: var(--fs-sm);
		font-weight: 700;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		letter-spacing: 0.03em;
		color: var(--color-text);
		margin-bottom: 10px;
	}

	.example-content {
		background: var(--color-surface);
		border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
		border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
		padding: 12px;
		font-size: var(--fs-sm);
		font-family: monospace;
		line-height: 1.6;
	}

	.example-field {
		padding: 4px 0;
		border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);
	}

	.example-field:last-child {
		border-bottom: none;
	}

	.field-label {
		font-weight: 700;
		color: var(--color-text);
	}

	.example-note {
		font-size: var(--fs-sm);
		color: var(--color-text-muted);
		margin-top: 10px;
		line-height: 1.6;
	}

	.stats-grid {
		display: flex;
		gap: 16px;
		margin: 16px 0;
		flex-wrap: wrap;
	}

	.stat-item {
		flex: 1;
		min-width: 140px;
		background: var(--color-surface);
		border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
		border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
		padding: 14px;
		text-align: center;
	}

	.stat-item.stat-bad {
		border-color: #dc3545;
		background: #fff5f5;
	}

	.stat-item.stat-bad .stat-number {
		color: #dc3545;
	}

	.stat-number {
		display: block;
		font-size: 28px;
		font-weight: 700;
		color: var(--color-accent);
		line-height: 1;
		margin-bottom: 6px;
	}

	.stat-desc {
		font-size: var(--fs-sm);
		color: var(--color-text-muted);
		line-height: 1.4;
	}

	.nav-link {
		display: inline-block;
		font-size: var(--fs-base);
		color: var(--color-blue);
		padding: 8px 20px;
		border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
		border-radius: var(--radius-md);
		transition:
			background var(--transition),
			border-color var(--transition);
	}

	.nav-link:hover {
		background: var(--color-blue-light);
		border-color: var(--color-blue);
		text-decoration: none;
	}

	@media (max-width: 768px) {
		.stats-grid {
			flex-direction: column;
		}

		.page-title {
			font-size: 22px;
		}
	}
</style>
